        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 22px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">What’s in a name?</h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          Victoria’s Secret wasn’t just designed for women; it was founded to make lingerie shopping easier for men. In the 1970s, lingerie stores were not very welcoming to male shoppers. <strong>Roy Raymond, the founder, experienced this awkwardness firsthand when he tried to buy lingerie as a gift for his wife</strong>. Saleswomen ignored him, and he felt like an intruder in the store. This discomfort sparked Raymond’s idea to revamp the lingerie shopping experience, which would eventually become a cult favorite.
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-image padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/bh-jan-18-1.png" alt="What’s in a name?" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          Determined to transform the lingerie industry, the Stanford graduate spent eight years studying the market. He identified two key issues: the lack of a male-friendly shopping environment and the absence of stylish, sensual lingerie. To address these, <strong>Raymond opened the first Victoria’s Secret store in Palo Alto, California, in 1977</strong>. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          <strong>Raymond’s strategy was to create a respectable and sophisticated narrative around lingerie shopping</strong>. The name "Victoria’s Secret" was <a href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-18-01-2025-inspired-by-the-victorian-era" target="_blank">inspired by the Victorian era</a>, giving it a sense of elegance. The "secret" in the name added intimacy and intrigue. The brand’s name was unlike the blunt and often crass names of other lingerie stores at the time. <strong>Some customers even believed Victoria was a real woman</strong> and sent letters, poems, and gift certificates addressed to her.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

 
