          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 22px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Intimate revolution</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          While traditional stores were filled with terry cloth robes and oversized floral-print nightgowns under harsh fluorescent lighting, <strong>Victoria's Secret stores were designed to resemble Victorian boudoirs</strong>. They created a luxurious, intimate atmosphere with dark wood paneling, plush rugs, and heavy curtains. The stores showcased silk, lace, and sheer fabrics, offering a striking departure from the functional yet dull options that dominated the market.
         </p>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-image padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/bh-jan-18-2.png" alt="Intimate revolution" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Victoria’s Secret launched its first mail-order catalog, a groundbreaking move. The catalog allowed customers to access stylish lingerie when the Internet was unavailable. <a href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-18-01-2025-the-glossy-catalog" target="_blank">The glossy catalog</a>, filled with alluring images of women in lace and silk, became essential to the brand’s success. <strong>In 1982, Raymond charged customers three dollars for the catalog, and catalog sales accounted for 55% of the company's sales that year</strong>.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Despite its early success, <strong>Victoria’s Secret faced financial struggles in the early 1980s</strong>. The brand’s focus on male customers had begun to alienate female shoppers. Seeing potential in the brand, Leslie Wexner, the businessman behind The Limited, bought it for what’s rumored to be as little as $1 million. Roy Raymond unknowingly handed over a goldmine. Wexner <strong>reclaimed Victoria’s Secret as a brand for women</strong>, positioning it between mass-market names like Jockey and luxury labels like La Perla, effectively filling a significant gap in the market.</p>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 22px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Wexner’s angels</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Under Wexner, the catalog transformed. What had become daring and overly sexualized under Raymond’s direction transformed into a tasteful, fashion-forward publication. It featured men and women models to attract their female customers. To further its image, Victoria’s Secret catalog’s were <strong>listing the company’s headquarters at a fake London address</strong> while the real headquarters were in Columbus, Ohio. Products like the iconic <a href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-18-01-2025-3-miracle-bra" target="_blank">Miracle Bra</a>, launched in 1993, became instant hits, selling 2 million units in its first year.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">The 1990s marked a turning point for Victoria’s Secret. The brand capitalized on the era of supermodels, featuring stars like Tyra Banks, Stephanie Seymour, and Helena Christensen in its catalogs. In <strong>1995, Wexner and Ed Razek introduced the Victoria’s Secret Fashion Show, which became a cultural phenomenon</strong>. These models walked the ramp in the iconic <a href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-18-01-2025-4-fantasy-bras" target="_blank">Fantasy Bras</a> that cost up to $1 million. The annual runway spectacle, featuring the <a href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-18-01-2025-5-angels" target="_blank">“Angels,”</a> ran from 1995 to 2018 and became incredibly popular, and everyone became familiar with Victoria’s Secret. Victoria’s Secret evolved from a small boutique into a global fashion brand, redefining lingerie as both a fashion statement and a daily essential.</p>
          </mj-text> 
      </mj-column>
  </mj-section> 

